title: For Sale/Trade:  1857 Enfield Tower
postcontent:
British Tower Enfield Pattern 1857 

Make: This musket is Tower marked, meaning it could have been made by any number of contractors.

Caliber: .629 Smoothbore (Possibly)

Action Type: This black powder, muzzle loading rifle uses a percussion (cap and ball) ignition system.

Markings: The rear of the lockplate is marked with a Crown over “VR” indicating it was made for British service during the reign of Queen Victoria (Victoria Regina). The front of the lockplate is marked with “1857 / TOWER”.  The barrel has a marking of “25” with another marking in front of it. The buttstock has a stamp a circular stamp on it with 2 or three words.

Barrel Length: The barrel is 33” in length.

Sights / Optics: The front sight is a short blade fixed to a rectangular base on the barrel. 
Stock Configuration & Condition: The stock is one piece walnut with a smooth straight grip, and brass furnishings (buttplate, nose cap and trigger guard.) The overall length of the stock is 48 ½” from the front of the nose cap to the back of the buttplate. There is a sling swivel attached to the front of the trigger guard, and the underside of the forend and the back edge of the nose cap are grooved for storing a ramrod under the barrel. There are numerous dings, bruises and gouges in the wood. The buttplate shows several compression marks and has developed a mustard colored patina. The buttplate is in about Good condition. The stock is in about Fair overall condition.

Type of Finish: The barrel and hammer were blued and we think the lock plate was case colored..

Finish Originality: The finish is original.

Bore Condition: The smooth bore is dark. There is erosion the length of the bore.

Overall Condition: This rifle retains about 20% of its metal finish. The barrel, lockplate and hammer have developed a very dark patina, which all show pitting, with solid erosion on the barrel along the edges of the wood and rust showing on and around the nipple. The barrel and hammer show surface loss under the patina with spots of bluing scattered over their surface. The trigger guard shows a mustard colored patina with several compression marks. The screw heads are disfigured. The markings are very thin and partially obscured by erosion. Overall, this rifle rates in about Fair to Good condition.

Mechanics: The action functions correctly. The hammer has half-cock and full cock positions. We have not fired this rifle.

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: The rifle comes with a 33” two piece ramrod stored under the front receiver. The rod shows several small spots of tarnish. The cleaning rod is in about Very Good condition.

Very motivated to sell.  Very flexible on price.

title: For Sale:  Lee Enfield (303 British - Fazakerley factory in Liverpool ) MK1 NO4 with Bayonet & Sling
postcontent:
- 303 British Lee Enfield MK4 NO1 with bolt, barrel, & furniture with matching serial #'s. - 

*** This has original full furniture with matching (serial #'s) furniture, bolt, and barrel. The magazine reflects F48 which matches the stamp on the barrel (F) and year (48). The symbol (Arrow stamp) is known as the “Broad Arrow“, there are many variations and it may be found with other markings. It denotes acceptance / issue as a military rifle into a specific country or it's own and the Fazakerley factory in Liverpool No.4 rifles had the # 2 or II / PF letter prefixes as this rifle reflects. The Lee–Enfield bolt-action, magazine-fed, repeating rifle was the main firearm used by the military forces of the British Empire and Commonwealth. It featured a ten-round box magazine which was loaded with the .303 British cartridge manually from the top, either one round at a time or by means of five-round chargers. The Lee–Enfield was the standard issue weapon to rifle companies of the British Army and other Commonwealth nations in both the First and Second World Wars (these Commonwealth nations included Australia, New Zealand, Canada and South Africa, among others). It was the British Army's standard rifle from its official adoption in 1895 until 1957 and became known as  "three-oh-three". For the price, it is a great deal for a WWII rifle. ***
